#Text=Katya Komisaruk
#Text=Katya Komisaruk is an American civil rights lawyer and social justice activist .
#Text=She attended Harvard Law School , helped form the Midnight Special Law Collective and Just Cause Law Collective . [ 1 ] [ 2 ]
#Text=Early years
#Text=As a child in Detroit , Michigan , Komisaruk was inspired by reading about the White Rose group who resisted Nazism in Germany .

#Text=" It was important to me to know that not everybody was wrong , that there were some people who did the right thing even when everybody else was failing to stop the train " , she says about this early influence . [ 3 ]
#Text=Komisaruk attended Reed College and began an MBA program at the University of California , Berkeley .

#Text=On June 2 , 1987 Komisaruk broke into the Vandenberg Air Force Base and destroyed a mainframe computer that she believed to be part of a U.S. first-strike nuclear launch system , NAVSTAR . [ 4 ]
#Text=From an Los Angeles Times article that year :
#Text=She broke into the building and for two hours trashed a million-dollar mainframe IBM 3031 computer , hacking away at it with crowbar , bolt cutters , hammer and cordless drill .

#Text=She danced on the computer chips she had pried loose , spray-painted the casing walls with slogans such as " International Law , " " Nuremberg " and " Defense of Necessity , " and climbed to the roof to take similar action against a satellite dish .

column1: #Text=An extensive interview with her about the incident was published in 1988 . [ 5 ]
#Text=While serving a 5-year sentence , Komisaruk studied for the Law School Admission Test ( LSAT ) and in 1990 gained acceptance to Harvard Law School the same week she was paroled .
#Text=Career
#Text=Komisaruk helped represent 600 defendants arrested in the 1999 Seattle WTO protests , mostly accused of " failure to disperse " . [ 6 ]

#Text=As a volunteer for Direct Action Network , she suggested a solidarity tactic in which the alleged protestors clog the courts by insisting on a jury trial , unless the City Attorney Mark Sidran agree to a blanket deal in which all defendants are given the same treatment .
#Text=92 % of the cases were dropped , and the prosecution only brought six cases to trial .
#Text=Five of the tried defendants were acquitted , and the one conviction resulted in community service and a small fine .

#Text=In the follow-on 2000 Washington , D.C. protests against the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund ( IMF ) , Komisaruk used a similar approach to get approximately 1,300 activists released with a $ 5 fine .
#Text=In Los Angeles , activists were arrested over three days during the 2000 Democratic National Convention protests .
#Text=Komisaruk documents that 50 people used solidarity tactics , refused to give their names , and went on a hunger strike until a universal plea bargain was worked out .
#Text=The activists were released with suspended sentences in consideration of time served , and the prosecutor went on to publicly commend the protestors ' integrity and commitment .
#Text=Leaving the Midnight Special Law Collective in 2000 , Komisaruk formed Just Cause Law Collective , specializing in activist support and defense . [ 2 ]
#Text=The organization later became " Causa Justa : : Just Cause " , which has changed laws in favor of renters , and fights evictions in Oakland , California .

#Text=Komisaruk 's defense of a client accused of prostitution , who was caught in an undercover sting operation in Oakland , California in 2003 , helped catalyze Robyn Few 's bid to legalize prostitution in California . [ 7 ]
#Text=Few went on to form Sex Workers Outreach Project USA , and the Just Cause Law Collective 's " Know Your Rights " materials are used to educate sex workers about their legal rights .
